docs/api/Component.html.body:
Component
Component classes ready to be embedded as JSX for rendering.
Usage
/** @jsx h */
import { createComponent, h } from 'frint';

const MyComponent = createComponent({
  render() {
    return (
      Name is {this.prop.name}
    );
  }
});

It is best practice to define propTypes while defining the Component too. You can read more about it in PropTypes section.

docs/api/mapToProps.html.body:
mapToProps
This is a handy function that is used for enhancing your Components, by injecting new values as props coming in from various sources.
State
If you want to get values from state, and bind the values as they change to your Component as props, you can:
/** @jsx h */
import { createComponent, mapToProps, h } from 'frint';

const MyComponent = createComponent({
  render() {
    const { todos } = this.props;

    return (...); // JSX here
  }
});

export default mapToProps({
  state: (state) => {
    todos: state.todos.records
  }
})(MyComponent);

Actions
/** @jsx h */
import { createComponent, mapToProps, h } from 'frint';

import { addTodo } from '../actions/todos';

const MyComponent = createComponent({
  render() {
    const { handleAddButton } = this.props;

    return (...); // JSX here
  }
});

export default mapToProps({
  dispatch: {
    handleAddButton: addTodo
  }
})(MyComponent);

App
If you want to inject something coming from the App instance:
export default mapToProps({
  app: (app) => {
    return {
      appName: app.getOption('name')
    };
  }
})(MyComponent);

Models can be accessed as:
export default mapToProps({
  app: (app) => {
    return {
      color: app
        .getModel('shirt')
        .getColor()
    };
  }
})(MyComponent);

Shared state from other Apps
If you app is allwoed to listen to state changes happening in other Apps, you can:
export default mapToProps({
  shared: (sharedState) => {
    return {
      counter: sharedState.SomeOtherAppName[reducerName].someKey
    };
  }
})(MyComponent);

Services
export default mapToProps({
  services: {
    // propName: serviceKeyName
    http: 'http'
  }
})(MyComponent);

Factories
export default mapToProps({
  factories: {
    // propName: factoryKeyName
    request: 'request'
  }
})(MyComponent);

Observe
The observe key can be used for listening to an observable, and then map its returned object as props.
You have access to the app instance, leaving you free to get observables from other Factories or Services if need be
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';

export default mapToProps({
  observe: (app) => {
    return Observable
      // iterate over these values in a sequence
      .of(1, 2)

      // now convert it to an object, which will be available as props
      .scan(
        // this function would be called twice,
        // first with `1`, and then `2` as number
        (props, number) => {
          props.total = props.total + number;

          return acc;
        },

        // the initial object to start the `scan` with
        {
          name: app.getOption('name'),
          total: 0
        }
      );
  }
})(RootComponent);

docs/api/Region.html.body:
Region
Region is a oberservable-ready Component, that is exposed for Core app's convenience.
When you embed this Component with a given name, any time other apps register themselves to that named region, they will appear inside that relevantly named Region.
Example
/** @jsx h */
import { createComponent, Region, h } from 'frint';

const MyComponent = createComponent({
  render() {
    return (

        Below is the sidebar region:



    );
  }
});

Next time, when a new Widget gets loaded, and it calls setRegion:
someChildApp.setRegion('sidebar');

...our Region defined in Core app's MyComponent would re-render accordingly.
